body:
I hit a situation where `PrefixModules` should be duplicating modules, but it is not.

Consider the following:

```
circuit Top : %[[
  {
    "class":"sifive.enterprise.firrtl.NestedPrefixModulesAnnotation",
    "target":"~Top|Foo",
    "prefix":"A_",
    "inclusive":true
  },
  {
    "class":"sifive.enterprise.firrtl.NestedPrefixModulesAnnotation",
    "target":"~Top|Foo_1",
    "prefix":"B_",
    "inclusive":true
  },
  {
    "class": "firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation",
    "target": "~Top|Foo>in"
  },
  {
    "class": "firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation",
    "target": "~Top|Foo_1>in"
  }
]]
  module Foo :
    input in : UInt<8>

  module Foo_1 :
    input in : UInt<8>

  module Top :
    input in : UInt<8>

    inst f1 of Foo
    inst f2 of Foo_1
    f1.in <= in
    f2.in <= in
```

If I run this with `firtool -dedup`, I get the following Verilog:

```verilog
module A_Foo(
  input [7:0] in);

endmodule

module Top(
  input [7:0] in);

  A_Foo f1 (
    .in (in)
  );
  A_Foo f2 (
    .in (in)
  );
endmodule
```

If I run without dedup, I get two modules (expectedly):

```verilog
module A_Foo(
  input [7:0] in);

endmodule

module B_Foo_1(
  input [7:0] in);

endmodule

module Top(
  input [7:0] in);

  A_Foo f1 (
    .in (in)
  );
  B_Foo_1 f2 (
    .in (in)
  );
endmodule
```

Basically, I'm expecting to see both an `A_` and `B_` prefix in the output and I only get an `A_` prefix.
